---
import GuideLayout from "../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro";

const title = "CloudFront pricing: a practical way to estimate bandwidth and request costs";
const description =
  "A practical guide to estimating CloudFront-style CDN costs using bandwidth (GB/month) and request fees, without relying on hardcoded prices.";
---
<GuideLayout title={title} description={description} canonicalPath="/guides/aws-cloudfront-pricing" lastUpdated="2026-01-20">
  <p>
    CloudFront-style CDN bills usually have two primary parts: <strong>bandwidth</strong> and <strong>requests</strong>.
    This guide explains how to estimate both in a way that stays stable as pricing changes.
  </p>

  <h2>1) Estimate bandwidth (GB/month)</h2>
  <p>
    Use CDN analytics if you have them. If you only have throughput charts (Mbps), convert Mbps to GB/month using the
    <a href="/calculators/unit-converter/">Units Converter</a> or follow
    <a href="/guides/estimate-cdn-bandwidth-gb-per-month/">this bandwidth estimation guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>2) Estimate request volume (requests/month)</h2>
  <p>
    If you have a request count from logs/analytics, use it directly. If you have RPS, convert it to monthly requests
    with <a href="/calculators/rps-to-monthly-requests-calculator/">RPS to Monthly Requests</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>3) Apply pricing assumptions</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Bandwidth line item: GB/month × $/GB (use a blended rate if pricing tiers apply).</li>
    <li>Request line item: (requests/month ÷ 10k) × $ per 10k.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>4) Common pitfalls</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Mixing GB and GiB units across dashboards and pricing pages.</li>
    <li>Ignoring tiered pricing (use blended rates or scenario modeling).</li>
    <li>Forgetting origin egress/cache fill when your hit rate is low.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Related calculators</h2>
  <p>
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/cloudfront-cost-calculator/">CloudFront cost calculator</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/calculators/cdn-cost-calculator/">CDN cost calculator</a>
    <a class="btn" href="/guides/origin-egress-vs-cdn-bandwidth/">Origin egress vs CDN bandwidth</a>
  </p>
</GuideLayout>

